John<br>
Cool, we were lucky to get ammo. Don't know why the Corps never had enough supplies on hand, except ammo, plenty of ammo. We had to trade for anything else we needed or wanted including rain gear, or cleaning gear for our weapons. <br>
That's why we were always ripping off the Sea Bees, Air Force and Army bases, for what ever supplies we could get. I remember walking into an Air Force base it might have been in Chu Lai and seeing mattresses on real bunks. What a life. Even the rubber lady's we obtained had to be bartered for (oh! that doesn't sound good). Guess you know what I mean.<br><br>
SW, <br>
Operation Knox, one of our Marine snipers kept popping gooks climbing up along side a parallel mountainside as we raced them to where a puff plane had been shot down. He always shot them in the head. A couple of months later, ironically a gook sniper shot him in the head. I found a lot of irony in Nam. A lot of things happened that cannot be explained sometimes I believed we had to draw from our past before we could have hope for the future.  Your story also reminded me about Nasty Nick and Quick Draw one day I'll share their two stories here.  <br><br>
A lot of supernatural stuff also happened in Nam that cannot be explained. I know of  two mother's of Marines in our unit who on the day their sons were killed awoke to a dream where sons appeared to tell them they had been shot. I believe Ed mentioned spirituality, but the text books have also left this out. <br><br>

